SIMPLE: peach
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Peach
<hw>Peach</hw> <pr>(p⟦emac⟧ch)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Appeach</er>, <er>Impeach</er>.]</ety> <def>To accuse of crime; to
inform against.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Foxe.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peach</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Peach
<hw>Peach</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To turn informer; to betray one's
accomplice.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If I be ta'en, I'll <qex>peach</qex> for this.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peach</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Peach
<hw>Peach</hw> <pr>(p⟦emac⟧ch)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>peche</ets>, <ets>peshe</ets>, OF. <ets>pesche</ets>, F.
<ets>p⟦ecir⟧che</ets>, fr. LL. <ets>persia</ets>, L. <ets>Persicum</ets>
(sc. <ets>malum</ets>) a Persian apple, a peach. Cf. <er>Persian</er>,
and <er>Parsee</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A
well-known high-flavored juicy fruit, containing one or two seeds in a
hard almond-like endocarp or stone. In the wild stock the fruit is hard
and inedible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The tree (<spn>Prunus Persica</spn> syn.
<spn>Amygdalus Persica</spn>) which bears the peach fruit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The pale red <isa>color</isa> of the peach blossom,
or the light pinkish yellow of the peach fruit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Guinea peach</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Sierra
Leone peach</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the large edible berry of the
<spn>Sarcocephalus esculentus</spn>, a rubiaceous climbing shrub of west
tropical Africa.</cd> -- <col><b>Palm peach</b></col>, <cd>the fruit of
a Venezuelan palm tree (<spn>Bactris speciosa</spn>).</cd> --
<col><b>Peach color</b></col>, <cd>the pale red color of the peach
blossom.</cd> -- <col><b>Peach-tree borer</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>,
<cd>the larva of a clearwing moth (<spn>Aegeria exitiosa</spn>,
<it>or</it> <spn>Sannina, exitiosa</spn>) of the family
<fam>Aegeriidae</fam>, which is very destructive to peach trees by
boring in the wood, usually near the ground; also, the moth itself. See
<xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Borer</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peachblow</ent>⟦br⟧
